Conductor-Task: Phase 5 / Step 2 - Expo Web Export and Vercel Deployment Configuration
Conductor-Summary: Ran npx expo export -p web; blocked twice before succeeding. (1) An accidental full system PATH dump had been captured as a line in the local .env (untracked/gitignored), tripping Expo's "dangerous environment variables" guard - removed that single line, no other .env content touched. (2) app.json had web.output: "static", which assumes expo-router and triggered its static-rendering pipeline even though this project uses @react-navigation/native-stack (no expo-router dependency); changed to "single" for a standard SPA bundle. (3) react-native-google-mobile-ads (imported in App.tsx, AdBanner.tsx, HomeScreen.tsx, useInterstitialAd.ts) is native-only and its codegenNativeComponent import cannot be resolved by Metro on web; added metro.config.js with a resolver.resolveRequest override that redirects this package to a new web-safe stub (src/lib/mobileAdsWebStub.ts, mirroring BannerAd/BannerAdSize/TestIds/InterstitialAd/AdEventType/mobileAds() as no-ops) only when platform === 'web'. After these fixes, npx expo export -p web succeeded, producing dist/ (index.html, _expo/static/js/web bundle, assets) — gitignored, not committed. Created vercel.json with SPA rewrites (all routes -> /index.html) to prevent 404s on refreshing sub-routes like /paywall or /action-plan, plus immutable cache headers for _expo static assets and buildCommand/outputDirectory wired to the Expo web export. Vercel CLI (vercel@54.18.6, installed via npx) has no local credentials (ercel whoami fails) - did not attempt ercel login or --prod deploy since that requires interactive user authentication; documented the manual Vercel project configuration instead (Framework: Other, Build Command: npx expo export -p web, Output Directory: dist, Install Command: npm install). Verified npx tsc --noEmit (0 errors).
